## R Perspective Plot: `persp()`

:::: {.columns}

::: {.column width="44%"}

::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

:::

::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code  code-line-numbers="false"}
par(mar = c(0,0,0,0))
# Exaggerate the relief
z <- 2 * volcano      
# 10 meter spacing (S to N)
x <- 10 * (1:nrow(z))   
# 10 meter spacing (E to W)
y <- 10 * (1:ncol(z))   
par(bg = "slategray")
persp(x, y, z, theta = 135, phi = 30, 
      col = "green3", scale = FALSE,
      ltheta = -120, shade = 0.75, 
      border = NA, box = FALSE)
```
:::
:::



::: {.column width="56%"}

::: {.cell layout-align="center"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](images/06-syntax/unnamed-chunk-163-1.png){fig-align='center' width=100%}
:::
:::
:::
::::

In [Python](https://matplotlib.org/stable/plot_types/3D/surface3d_simple.html),

::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.python .cell-code  code-fold="true" code-line-numbers="false"}
volcano = pd.read_csv("./slides/data/volcano.csv", index_col=0)
volcano = volcano.values
z = 2 * volcano
x = np.arange(1, z.shape[0] + 1) * 10
y = np.arange(1, z.shape[1] + 1) * 10  
X, Y = np.meshgrid(y, x)
fig = plt.figure()
ax = fig.add_subplot(projection='3d', facecolor="slategray")
ax.plot_surface(X, Y, z, cmap="Greens", edgecolor="none", shade=True, alpha=0.9)
plt.show()
```
:::


::: notes
- You can also generate a so-called perspective plot using the function persp().
- I don't use the function often. You can try it with different argument values, and see how it changes.
:::


